Hi Thomas, 

I found an interesting glitch! You might like this :-)

Initial situation:
```
group multi_neighbor {
    process receive-routes {
        encoder json;
        run /opt/exabgp/bin/queuer.py /export/exabgp/message-queues/0;
        neighbor-changes;
        receive {
            update;
            parsed;
            packets;
            consolidate;
            open;
            keepalive;
            notification;
        }
    }
```
This is fine, our process receives state messages for a peer:
```
{ "exabgp": "3.4.8", "time": 1443032039.48, "host" : "rrc-test.ripe.net", "pid" : "29876", "ppid" : "1", "counter": 1, "type": "state", "neighbor": { "ip": "193.0.4.28", "address": { "local": "193.0.19.22", "peer": "193.0.4.28"}, "asn": { "local": "65000", "peer": "12654"}, "state": "connected"} }
{ "exabgp": "3.4.8", "time": 1443032041.1, "host" : "rrc-test.ripe.net", "pid" : "29876", "ppid" : "1", "counter": 2, "type": "state", "neighbor": { "ip": "193.0.4.28", "address": { "local": "193.0.19.22", "peer": "193.0.4.28"}, "asn": { "local": "65000", "peer": "12654"}, "state": "up"} }
```
Then I add a second process, which only outputs neighbor-changes. So the config looks like this:
```
    process receive-routes {
        encoder json;
        run /opt/exabgp/bin/queuer.py /export/exabgp/message-queues/0;
        neighbor-changes;
        receive {
            update;
            parsed;
            packets;
            consolidate;
            open;
            keepalive;
            notification;
        }
    }
    process receive-moar-routes {
        encoder json;
        run /opt/exabgp/bin/queuer.py /export/exabgp/message-queues/0;
        neighbor-changes;
    }
```
Note it's actually a second instance of exactly the same process (this is just an example test).
Both processes now see one copy of the state messages each, which is what we would expect:
```
{ "exabgp": "3.4.8", "time": 1443032158.33, "host" : "rrc-test.ripe.net", "pid" : "29896", "ppid" : "1", "counter": 1, "type": "state", "neighbor": { "ip": "193.0.4.28", "address": { "local": "193.0.19.22", "peer": "193.0.4.28"}, "asn": { "local": "65000", "peer": "12654"}, "state": "connected"} }
{ "exabgp": "3.4.8", "time": 1443032158.33, "host" : "rrc-test.ripe.net", "pid" : "29896", "ppid" : "1", "counter": 2, "type": "state", "neighbor": { "ip": "193.0.4.28", "address": { "local": "193.0.19.22", "peer": "193.0.4.28"}, "asn": { "local": "65000", "peer": "12654"}, "state": "connected"} }
{ "exabgp": "3.4.8", "time": 1443032159.95, "host" : "rrc-test.ripe.net", "pid" : "29896", "ppid" : "1", "counter": 6, "type": "state", "neighbor": { "ip": "193.0.4.28", "address": { "local": "193.0.19.22", "peer": "193.0.4.28"}, "asn": { "local": "65000", "peer": "12654"}, "state": "up"} }
{ "exabgp": "3.4.8", "time": 1443032159.95, "host" : "rrc-test.ripe.net", "pid" : "29896", "ppid" : "1", "counter": 7, "type": "state", "neighbor": { "ip": "193.0.4.28", "address": { "local": "193.0.19.22", "peer": "193.0.4.28"}, "asn": { "local": "65000", "peer": "12654"}, "state": "up"} }
```
Now the weird part. We replace the second process with a new one which does *not* have 'neighbor-changes' enabled. In this case, it's a control socket that hooks up a socket listener so we can send commands to exabgp when necessary:
```
group multi_neighbor {
    process receive-routes {
        encoder json;
        run /opt/exabgp/bin/queuer.py /export/exabgp/message-queues/0;
        neighbor-changes;
        receive {
            update;
            parsed;
            packets;
            consolidate;
            open;
            keepalive;
            notification;
        }
    }
    process control-socket {
        run /opt/exabgp/bin/control_socket.run /var/run/exabgp/control_instance_0.sock;
    }
```
Now, the first process (receive-routes) no longer gets any 'state' messages!
It still receives all the updates/opens/keepalives/etc
But the first process stops getting any state messages when a second process is added, if the second process doesn't have neighbor-changes enabled.

This is on v3.4.12 btw.

It caused our later received route processing to go a bit haywire as we didn't see an initial connection state, which we use to initialise our RIB processor.

If you need any more info, please let me know!

Thanks as always,
Colin

